article.headline: Georgia 68, Presbyterian 58
article.story: ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Georgia scored only one field goal over the final 13 minutes but held off Presbyterian 68-58 on Sunday. Billy Humphrey scored 12 to lead the Bulldogs (8-3), including a fade-away with 13:33 to play that put Georgia up 59-34. But a layup by Dave Bliss with 9:07 to play was the only other field goal Georgia scored in the rest of the second half. Presbyterian (1-16), down by 29 early in the second half, was led by Bryan Bostic with 21 points. The Bulldogs led 10-0 before they even missed a field goal and scored the first 15 points of the game before Presbyterian scored five minutes into the game on a 3-pointer by Walt Allen. Georgia mounted another 8-0 run late in the first half to push the lead to 37-16 as Humphrey banked one in from the left side with 5:16 to go in the half. The Bulldogs were up 45-22 at halftime. A 15-2 run by the Blue Hose in the middle of the second half trimmed Georgia's lead to 59-46 after a 3-pointer by Bostic. Bostic hit a 3-pointer with 1:22 to play to cut the margin to 66-58, but Presbyterian could get no closer. Humphrey hit two of four free throws in the final minute to account for the final score. Georgia got 10 points each from Terrence Woodbury, Bliss and Jeremy Price. Sundiata Gaines gathered in 11 rebounds. Presbyterian was playing its eighth of 11 straight road games. Presbyterian is playing its first season in Division I. The Blue Hose will play in the Big South Conference next year. Presbyterian has only five home games this year in its front-end loaded schedule that ends Feb. 25.
